          "type": "exercise",
          "number": 1,
          "statement": "A circuit with inductance $L$ and capacitance $C$ satisfies $L\\frac{d^2q}{dt^2} + \\frac{q}{C} = 0$. Find the charge $q(t)$ if $q(0) = Q_0$ and $\\frac{dq}{dt}(0) = 0$.",
          "solution": {
            "steps": [
              {
                "title": "Rewrite",
                "content": "$\\frac{d^2q}{dt^2} + \\frac{1}{LC}q = 0$\n\nLet $\\omega_0 = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{LC}}$."
              },
              {
                "title": "Solve",
                "content": "$q = C_1 \\cos \\omega_0 t + C_2 \\sin \\omega_0 t$\n\n$q(0) = C_1 = Q_0$\n$q'(0) = \\omega_0 C_2 = 0 \\Rightarrow C_2 = 0$"
              }
            ],
            "conclusion": "$q = Q_0 \\cos\\left(\\frac{t}{\\sqrt{LC}}\\right)$"
          }
        },
